However, the description of the theorem is not complete. More precisely, it states that:

1. for every integer M, consisting of prime numbers;
2. there are only two prime integers p and q, for which p + q = M;
3. every prime p, which is not part of M, is derived from the two digits of M;
4. there is no prime that is not derived from the product of the two digits of M;
5. M has only two derivatives for arbitrary digits in M;
6. M has only one element from the class of (p+q) or (p-q) for every two digits p and q;
7. M has only one element from the class of (p^n-q^n) for every n-digit fraction p and q;
8. M has only two elements from the class of (p^n+q^n) for every n-digit fraction p and q;
9. The element from the class (p^n+q^n) entirely determines the class (p^n-q^n);
10. There is only one prime pxd/qxd, for which xxd>0 and pxd>0 and qxd>0;
11. M has only two prime numbers obtained by dividing by 4;
12. M has only two prime numbers by dividing by 5; and so on.

